3:["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"MEXC calculates SHIB/USDT funding rates every 8 hours at 00:00, 08:00, and 16:00 UTC, based on the premium between perpetual and spot prices. The exchange uses a time-weighted average price methodology with a ±0.05% dampening mechanism to prevent extreme rates. Position holders pay or receive funding based on their long/short exposure, with settlements occurring automatically without affecting margin requirements."}]
4:["$","section",null,{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":["Why ","SHIB","/","USDT","?"]}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"SHIB's high retail participation creates predictable funding rate patterns, with long bias during social media hype cycles generating positive rates exceeding 0.01% per funding period. MEXC's first-to-list strategy and zero maker fees provide cost-efficient entry for arbitrage strategies targeting SHIB's sentiment-driven price movements."}]]}]
5:["$","section","0",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Historical SHIB Funding Patterns on MEXC"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"SHIB funding rates on MEXC exhibit strong correlation with social sentiment and broader meme token rallies, often spiking above 0.02% during viral phases. The token shows distinct patterns around Ethereum network upgrades and Shibarium developments, with funding typically turning negative during extended bear markets. MEXC's retail-heavy user base amplifies these trends, creating more pronounced rate swings compared to institutional-focused exchanges. Historical data shows SHIB funding rates averaging 0.005% during neutral periods but reaching extremes of ±0.075% during high-volatility events."}]]}]
6:["$","section","1",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Arbitrage Opportunities and Zero Fee Advantage"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"MEXC's zero maker fee structure eliminates the primary cost barrier for SHIB funding arbitrage, allowing profitable strategies even at moderate funding rates above 0.003%. The exchange's aggressive SHIB promotion and listing incentives create temporary inefficiencies exploitable through cross-exchange funding spreads. High leverage up to 125x on SHIB perpetuals enables capital-efficient arbitrage, though position sizing must account for the token's inherent volatility. The 8-hour funding frequency provides three daily opportunities to capture rate premiums, particularly effective during Asia trading hours when MEXC volume peaks."}]]}]
7:["$","section","2",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Risk Management for SHIB Funding Strategies"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"SHIB's meme token nature introduces unique risks including extreme volatility spikes that can overwhelm funding profits, requiring strict position sizing below 2% portfolio exposure. MEXC's thinner order books compared to tier-1 exchanges create slippage risks during rapid unwinding, necessitating smaller position sizes and gradual exits. Regulatory uncertainty around MEXC operations poses counterparty risk, while the exchange's volume reporting questions suggest careful verification of actual liquidity. Successful SHIB funding arbitrage requires hedging spot exposure and maintaining sufficient margin buffers given the token's propensity for gap moves exceeding 20%."}]]}]
8:["$","$Ld",null,{"items":[{"question":"What makes SHIB funding rates on MEXC different from other exchanges?","answer":"MEXC's retail-heavy user base and zero maker fees create more volatile SHIB funding rates compared to institutional exchanges. The platform's aggressive meme token promotion amplifies long bias during hype cycles, often producing higher positive funding rates that can exceed 0.02% per 8-hour period."},{"question":"How do MEXC's zero maker fees impact SHIB funding arbitrage profitability?","answer":"Zero maker fees eliminate the primary cost component of funding arbitrage, making strategies profitable at funding rates as low as 0.003% compared to 0.008% required on traditional fee exchanges. This advantage is particularly significant for high-frequency SHIB arbitrage given the token's volatile funding patterns requiring frequent position adjustments."},{"question":"What are the main risks of SHIB funding arbitrage on MEXC?","answer":"Primary risks include SHIB's extreme volatility potentially overwhelming funding profits, MEXC's thinner liquidity creating slippage during exits, and regulatory uncertainty around the exchange's operations. The meme token's correlation with social sentiment can cause rapid funding rate reversals that require immediate position management."},{"question":"How should I size positions for SHIB funding strategies on MEXC?","answer":"Limit SHIB exposure to maximum 2% of portfolio given the token's volatility, with individual funding positions sized to withstand 25% adverse price moves without margin calls. MEXC's order book depth should be verified before large positions, typically keeping individual trades under $10,000 equivalent to ensure reasonable execution."}]}]
